# ESER v1.0 — EEE Studio Execution Runtime

```text id="eser-001"
# ============================================
# EEE STUDIO EXECUTION RUNTIME
# ESER v1.0
# ============================================

## PURPOSE

ESER is the execution engine that transforms ESS (Enterprise System Specification) into:

• Agent Systems
• Workflows
• Event Graphs
• API Contracts
• Runtime Configurations

It is NOT a framework.

It is NOT a prompt processor.

It is a deterministic system compiler for enterprise AI systems.

--------------------------------------------------

## CORE PRINCIPLE

Specification → Validation → Compilation → Execution Graph

No execution without validation.

No generation without structure.

No runtime without specification.

--------------------------------------------------

## INPUT

ESER accepts ONLY:

SYSTEM_SPEC (ESS v1.0 format)

Any unstructured input MUST be rejected.

--------------------------------------------------

## OUTPUT

ESER produces a SYSTEM PACKAGE:

SYSTEM_PACKAGE {
    agent_registry
    execution_graph
    workflow_engine
    event_bus
    api_gateway_spec
    data_layer_spec
    security_layer_spec
    runtime_config
    orchestration_plan
    deployment_blueprint
}
```

---

# 1. COMPILATION PIPELINE

```text id="eser-pipeline"
PIPELINE:

1. PARSE
   → Read ESS structure

2. VALIDATE
   → Schema validation
   → Domain validation
   → Consistency validation

3. NORMALIZE
   → Standardize naming
   → Resolve references

4. BUILD GRAPH
   → Agents graph
   → Event graph
   → Workflow graph

5. GENERATE ARTIFACTS
   → APIs
   → Data models
   → Contracts

6. ORCHESTRATE
   → Execution flow
   → Dependency resolution

7. PACKAGE
   → Final system bundle
```

---

# 2. AGENT COMPILATION ENGINE

```text id="eser-agents"
AGENT COMPILATION RULES:

For each role in ESS:

→ Create Agent Definition

Agent {
    id
    role_mapping

    capabilities
    inputs
    outputs

    event_subscriptions
    event_publications

    memory_model
    tool_access

    execution_constraints
    failure_policy
}
```

---

# 3. GRAPH BUILDER

```text id="eser-graph"
SYSTEM GRAPH TYPES:

1. Agent Interaction Graph
2. Event Flow Graph
3. Workflow State Graph
4. API Dependency Graph

RULES:
- No orphan nodes
- No circular dependencies (unless explicitly allowed)
- All flows must be traceable
```

---

# 4. VALIDATION ENGINE (CRITICAL)

```text id="eser-validation"
VALIDATION LAYERS:

1. Schema Validation
2. Domain Integrity Validation
3. Agent Consistency Validation
4. Event Integrity Validation
5. API Contract Validation
6. Workflow Consistency Validation
7. Security Compliance Validation
8. Orchestration Validation

FAIL POLICY:

IF validation fails:
→ STOP EXECUTION
→ RETURN ERROR REPORT
```

---

# 5. EVENT COMPILER

```text id="eser-events"
EVENT RULES:

For each domain event:

Event {
    name
    version
    source_agent
    target_agents
    payload_schema
    correlation_model
}

RULES:
- Immutable events only
- Versioned schema required
- Must have producer + consumer
```

---

# 6. WORKFLOW COMPILER

```text id="eser-workflow"
WORKFLOW MODEL:

Workflow {
    states
    transitions
    triggers
    agents_involved
    events_triggered
    compensation_rules
}

RULES:
- Every state must be reachable
- Every transition must be valid
- No silent transitions
```

---

# 7. API COMPILER

```text id="eser-api"
API GENERATION RULES:

For each capability:

API Contract {
    endpoint
    method
    request_schema
    response_schema
    error_schema
    security_policy
    version
}

RULES:
- Contract-first mandatory
- Versioning required
- Backward compatibility enforced
```

---

# 8. RUNTIME GENERATION

```text id="eser-runtime"
RUNTIME CONFIG:

runtime {
    execution_mode: deterministic

    orchestration_engine: graph_based

    context_isolation: strict

    event_bus: enabled

    observability: full

    failure_handling: {
        retry: controlled
        compensation: enabled
    }
}
```

---

# 9. ORCHESTRATION ENGINE

```text id="eser-orch"
ORCHESTRATION RULES:

- Global dependency graph execution
- No parallel conflict execution
- Event-driven coordination
- State-aware scheduling
- Conflict resolution required
```

